This course focuses on epidemiologic methods required to investigate urgent public health problems. 
These problems can range from infectious disease outbreaks to cancer clusters to chemical spills and environmental contamination. 
Students will learn the skills needed to conduct outbreak investigations and communicate findings to the public. 
This course introduces the basic steps of an outbreak investigation as well as specific skills such as 
creating questionnaires and epidemic curves, generating, and testing hypotheses, reviewing the literature, 
descriptive data analysis, and communicating during and after an outbreak. 
Student teams will facilitate weekly discussions. Assignments in the course are designed for collaborative and active
learning. This course is designed with flexibility and autonomy in mind. Teamwork is also strongly valued.
